	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=item.html?item=3981&mid=104932646875615>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=item.html?item=3981&mid=104932646875615>RE: question</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=3981&mid=104932646875615#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Apr 2nd 7:10 PM 2003</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=97875><span id=Scholar>verucali</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>25 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.25]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The effect of ATK is relatively small compared to the noisiness of the random number generator, which means that there isn't any conclusive parse data (at least, not that I've been able to find) that establishes the value of ATK and the general shape of the curve (for example, does 10 marginal points of ATK have a bigger impact at ATK 1000 or ATK 1400?). The best read I've found on the topic is <a href="http://forums.interealms.com/ranger/showthread.php?threadid=9616" target=_new>http://forums.interealms.com/ranger/showthread.php?threadid=9616</a><br><br>With all those caveats aside... the most common rule of thumb is that 10ATK = 1% damage increase. And while there is a point of diminishing returns on ATK that is dependent on the mob, any mob where your ATK is &quot;soft-capped&quot; is a mob that you wouldn't be wasting your time killing in the first place. And this is why ATK rules: as you get to be around level 60, it is relatively easy to hit the (soft) AC and (hard) stat caps - but more ATK keeps letting you do more damage.</p>&nbsp;<br>[58 Ranger] Verucali Volcani (Half Elf) &lt;House Bloodthorne&gt; Drinal</td></td></tr>
